# AI Pairing Context: distributed-lottery-analyser

## Project Overview
A highly parallelized, distributed application designed to run on top of the custom `distributed-compute-operator` which has already been created at https://github.com/Rosalita/distributed-compute-operator

This project has one main goal using the complete historical datasets (including prize breakdowns) for major UK National Lottery games (Lotto, Euromillions, Thunderball, and Set For Life):
1. **Most Profitable Line Finder:** Distribute the total possible combination space across worker pods to brute-force evaluate every single possible ticket against all historical draws, finding the specific line for each game that would have paid out the most total money over all time.

---

## Architecture (Tightly-Coupled Distributed Workload)
This application is packaged as a single Docker container but uses its networking hostname to determine its role at runtime.

### The Leader Pod (`<job-name>-leader`)
- **Data Manager:** Loads the historical datasets (winning numbers and prize values per tier) for all lottery games into memory on startup.
- **Global Observer & Dispatcher:** Assigns chunks of the total combination space (ranks) to connecting workers. Runs a gRPC server to receive and aggregate the highest-earning lines found by the workers.

### The Worker Pods (`<job-name>-worker-X`)
- **Combination Chunk Processing:** Each worker pod receives a specific subset of the millions of possible ticket combinations (represented as a flat range of ranks `[StartRank, EndRank)`) from the leader.
- **Historical Evaluation:** Workers rapidly simulate playing their assigned combinations across every historical draw, calculating the total monetary payout for each line based on historical prize tiers.
- **Result Reporting:** Once a worker finishes evaluating its chunk, it sends the top-earning lines and their total historical profit back to the leader over gRPC.

---

## Progress So Far
- **Infrastructure:** Custom Kubernetes Operator is complete and tested in the `distributed-compute-operator` repository.
- **Project Licensing & Normalization:**
  - Added MIT License under 2026 Rosalita.
  - Added `.gitattributes` to enforce consistent LF line endings repository-wide.
- **Data Gathering:** Built a standalone data-gathering script (`cmd/getdrawhistory`) that:
  - Fetches the latest 180-day summary CSVs and merges them into deduplicated CSV files.
  - Downloads the detailed prize breakdown JSON files for every historical draw with smart caching.
- **Data Loading:** Created `cmd/analyser/internal/data` package to successfully load historical draw JSON files into memory at startup.
- **Core Logic & Mathematical Engine (Stage 1 - Complete & Verified):**
  - **Combinadics (`internal/evaluator/combinadics.go`):** Implemented pre-computed binomial coefficients (Pascal's triangle) and unranking logic. Added `UnrankTicket` to map a 64-bit integer rank index to distinct primary/secondary ticket slices.
  - **Masking (`internal/evaluator/masking.go`):** Implemented `SliceToMask` to convert number slices to `uint64` bitmasks.
  - **Evaluator (`internal/evaluator/evaluator.go`):** Implemented `NewFastDraw` (parsing draws to `uint64` bitmasks and a static 2D lookup matrix `[matchPrimary][matchSecondary]`) and `EvaluateRange` (a zero-allocation matching loop using `math/bits.OnesCount64` / CPU `POPCNT` instruction).
  - **Modular Unit Tests:** Created `combinadics_test.go`, `masking_test.go`, and `evaluator_test.go` using a map-based table testing format. Test assertions are strictly non-tautological (utilizing explicit binary literals, e.g., `0b101010`). All tests pass successfully.

---

## Approved Plan & Next Stages for Development

The project is being built in small, incremental stages as tracked in the local task checklist (`task.md`).

### Stage 2: gRPC Setup & Code Generation (Next Step)
- Add gRPC and protobuf dependencies to `go.mod`.
- Write the protobuf schema `proto/analyser.proto`:
  - `RegisterWorker`: Worker registers with leader and receives the game configuration plus all historical draw data (to keep the worker stateless and avoid volume mounts).
  - `GetWork`: Issues range chunks to workers.
  - `ReportResult`: Workers report the top tickets found within their assigned range.
- Compile protobuf to Go gRPC client/server code using `protoc`.

### Stage 3: Leader Coordinator Server
- Implement the coordinator logic on the Leader (`internal/coordinator/leader.go`) to split the combination space into equal ranges, track worker registration, monitor chunk states (Unassigned, InProgress, Completed), handle worker disconnections/retries, and run the gRPC server.

### Stage 4: Worker Client
- Implement the Worker execution client (`internal/worker/worker.go`) to connect to the leader, request work ranges, run the evaluator core on the range, and report results back.

### Stage 5: Main Integration & Verification
- Update `cmd/analyser/main.go` to parse CLI flags (role, port, leader address, game name).
- Perform a local end-to-end integration test of Leader + Worker.

### Stage 6: Containerization & Deployment
- Write the `Dockerfile` for containerizing the application.
- Create the Kubernetes `DistributedJob` custom resource YAML to deploy the solver to the Kubernetes cluster using the `distributed-compute-operator`.